ted, the Nazis would not have had an easy occupation of the USSR.  But how effective would the opposition to the Nazis have been if Moscow had been taken out of the equation?<br>
<br>
Hitler was an idiot in the long run.  He relied on sharp, quick victories too much, which left him vulnerable to an extended campaign in Russia  and a record-breaking cold Russian winter for which his troops were not equipped for.  Remember, there are many factors in the equation, however.  Change a factor into the favor of the other side and the outcome is in doubt.<br>
<br>
Also, remember that it was not just Germanic people that served in the Axis armed forces.  The Nazis actively recruited for soldiers in many nations specifically to fight against communists (Finland and Turkey being notable examples).<br>
