<br>
Take out all American support before Pearl Harbor.  British convoys were being protected by American Naval warships, who were more than happy to engage German U-Boats as &quot;pirates&quot;...while the U-boats were under strict &quot;do-not enagage&quot; orders for all American shipping.  The US Navy was in all but name an active combatant long before Germany declared war on the US. <br>
<br>
Next, take away the American shipping that would take up the slack when Britain's ULTRA program redirected British convoys away from where ULTRA had pinpointed the wolfpacks.  Thanks to Hitler's absolute &quot;don't mess with the Yanks&quot; order, American freighters sailed through the Uboat's engagement areas unmolested before the German declaration of war on the US removed that restriction.<br>
<br>
<br>
Now take another look at the British Isles.  Take away up to half of the food that was being consumed by the British that was getting to the people of Britain via American shipping.<br>
<br>
Remember, Hitler didn't envision fighting the Allies until roughtly 1945, by which time he hoped to have a surface naval parity with the British.  When the Allies jumped Hitler's timetable after Poland, Hitler was left with just his Uboats and the possibility of starving Britain into submission.  It almost worked with the Americans playing loosey-goosey with being neutral.  It very well might have been otherwise if the Americans had been truly &quot;neutral&quot;. <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=187084"><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline"><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Colphax Moonleaf</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--></span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--></a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
