<br>
Let's clarify something:  The US was not at war with Germany until December 11th, 1941. Funny thing about the fact that trade between nations is only completely cut off when war is declared, idn't it?<br>
<br>
However, the Lend-Lease Act of 1941 was specifically written to supply war materials to Britain and China.  It was later expanded to include the USSR, which wasn't included originally thanks to sanctions in place in response to the USSR's invasion of Finland in 1939.  <br>
<br>
Off the top of my head, I can name weapon systems that went to Britain and Russia...but i don't remember any of them going to any of the Axis powers.  <br>
<br>
Buffalo fighter...Britain<br>
Aircobra fighter...Russians loved 'em, Americans didn't<br>
M3 Medium tank...also known as the Lee<br>
M5 Light Tank...also known as the Stuart<br>
<br>
Plus, the US also gave mothballed WW1 destroyers to the Brits.<br>
<br>
So, while I can't deny that the US traded war materials to both sides, I'd say that the amount traded to the eventual United Nations substantially dwarfed the amount that went to the Axis powers. <br>
<br>
So, Kerai, my question is, exactly what war materiel did the US ship to Germany?  Be specific, please. <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=187084"><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline"><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Colphax Moonleaf</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--></span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--></a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
